  "prompt": "Which mathematician solved the magic square problem?",
  "response": "The magic square problem has a long history and has been studied by many mathematicians over the centuries. A magic square is a square grid filled with distinct integers in such a way that the sum of the numbers in each row, column, and diagonal is the same. \n\nOne of the earliest known magic squares is attributed to the Chinese mathematician Chen Sheng in the 2nd century BCE, and the concept has been explored in various cultures, including India and the Islamic world.\n\nIn the context of modern mathematics, the construction and classification of magic squares were significantly advanced by mathematicians like Leonhard Euler in the 18th century. Euler introduced systematic methods for constructing magic squares, including the use of specific algorithms.\n\nTherefore, rather than a single mathematician solving the magic square problem, it has been a collective effort over centuries with contributions from many individuals.",
